		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2016"></a><br><code>sle2016/paper18</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2016</a> paper:</span><br><i>Side Effects Take the Blame</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/FelipeBañadosSchwerter.html">Felipe Bañados Schwerter</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2997364.2997381">10.1145/2997364.2997381</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagM">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> It develops gradual effect systems, i.e., static semantics for tracking side effects with gradual guarantees.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a><ul><li> Blame strategies are defined at the semantic level for when runtime checks fail.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> The framework combines static and dynamic checking, involving runtime enforcement mechanisms.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> It formalizes properties/strategies for blame in gradual effect systems, aligning with formal-methods-style reasoning.
</li></ul></li></ul>
